WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:08.000
Sarah and I are once again here to compare Posit Assistant to a different agent.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:14.000
A few weeks ago, we recorded this video comparing Posit Assistant to Cloud Code,

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:20.000
and today we're going to be comparing Posit Assistant to Positron Assistant.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:25.000
If you're feeling confused already, that's sort of why we're here.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:34.000
Posit Assistant and Positron Assistant are two different agents with two different lineages that just happen to have very similar names.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:42.000
But we know this has caused some confusion, so we figured we'd get together and talk about how they're similar and how they're different.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:55.000
To kick off that conversation, I wanted to start with just trying to very clearly talk through the history of Posit Assistant, Positron Assistant, and DataBot.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:05.000
Last year, inside of our Positron IDE, we introduced two agents pretty close to each other in the timeline.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:14.000
One of them is called DataBot, and DataBot is an AI agent for exploratory data analysis.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:28.000
Positron Assistant is also only available in Positron, and Positron Assistant is sort of like a general coding agent, but was also aware of what was happening in your IDE.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:38.000
At the time, both of those releases were targeting Positron. In our studio, there was not much to say.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:50.000
There were a few open-source packages out there that provided some AI assistance inside of the IDE, but really we were focused on features for Positron only.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:02:03.000
This year, we introduced a new agent called Posit Assistant, and for whatever reason, we made the decision to name it very similarly to one of those two agents.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:20.000
Posit Assistant supersedes both DataBot and Positron Assistant, and sort of merges those two agents along with a bunch of learnings that we've had through working on those two agents and using others.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:35.000
Posit Assistant, in this somewhat scrappy diagram, is shown inside of both Positron and RStudio because Posit Assistant is available in both of those IDEs.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:46.000
So while Positron Assistant and DataBot were only available in Positron, Posit Assistant is available in both Positron and RStudio.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:51.000
Sarah, have I mixed up Positron Assistant and Posit Assistant yet?

00:02:51.000 --> 00:03:00.000
No, I think that was all right. There are so many Posit words, and people internally will mix things up.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:22.000
Hopefully, I think it should improve going forward when we've solidified Posit Assistant, and then there's just Posit, Posit Assistant, Posit AI, which is still three Posits, but it's better, and Positron.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:34.000
Sarah has sort of seen what's coming next, which is that in these slides, I'm going to show DataBot and Positron Assistant going away.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:49.000
I have this listed as 2027, but at some point in the next year, those two tools will be superseded by Posit Assistant, and so it will just be that agent that's available in both IDEs.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:04:11.000
Another thing that she foreshadowed that is sort of confusing is that if you take away an apostrophe and an S, you have yet another name for a thing that is related to this space, which is Posit AI.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:35.000
Posit AI is a $20 a month subscription that gives you access to both Posit Assistant and NextEdit suggestions, so if you want to use Posit Assistant in RStudio, right now you need to use the Posit AI provider, which is offered through that subscription.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:45.000
And then in Positron, since we had allowed folks to bring their own keys to a bunch of different providers with Positron Assistant, we decided to continue supporting that in Positron.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:54.000
So through a subscription to Posit AI, you have access to Posit Assistant in RStudio.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:05:01.000
You can also use Posit AI with Posit Assistant in Positron, but you can bring other providers as well.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:08.000
Okay, the rest of this video, I'm going to be doing a little bit more demos, but it will come to you in two parts.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:19.000
In the first part, I'm going to try to convince you that they're very similar to each other, both Positron Assistant and Posit Assistant, so they have a lot of things in common.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:25.000
And then in the second half of the video, I'm going to show a bunch of ways that they're a little bit different from each other.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:35.000
Okay, so I think with this slide, we're now up to like five distinct fonts in this deck or something like that.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:42.000
I just want to call out some of the ways that Positron Assistant and Posit Assistant are pretty similar to each other.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:49.000
The first one is that they both support MCP or the Model Context Protocol.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:06:00.000
So the Model Context Protocol allows you to connect the agent to outside data sources, and both Positron Assistant and Posit Assistant support the full spec.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:07.000
Positron Assistant and Posit Assistant are both very customizable.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:17.000
So in Positron Assistant, you can use instructions, which are just text files with instructions that you want the agent to follow.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:21.000
There's also this concept of chat participants.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:27.000
Posit Assistant focuses on two open specifications.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:41.000
One of them is skills, which are portable MD files or scripts that the agent can choose to load in at any point to acquire some skill or learn about some more context.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:52.000
And then agents.md is similar to instructions files with GitHub Copilot or Claude.md with Claude or so on and so forth.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:56.000
Just plain text files that describe the behavior you want to see from the agent.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:04.000
Both Positron Assistant and Posit Assistant have a pretty rich permissions system.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:15.000
The only difference between Posit Assistant and Positron Assistant is that within a given tool, Posit Assistant allows you to vary the permissions.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:30.000
So for example, in the Bash tool, if the agent wants to git commit, I can allow that, but also require it to ask me to do something like git push.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:40.000
In Positron Assistant, the permissions would have to apply to the whole tool that is using git, which would be the Bash tool.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.000
And then finally, both of them support skills.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:50.000
So Positron Assistant will be getting this from upstream in VS Code pretty soon.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:08:05.000
In Posit Assistant, skills are built in, and we've shipped 10 or so built-in skills with the tool, in addition to allowing users to bring custom skills.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:17.000
So to help make the case that these agents are pretty similar to each other, I wanted to do a sort of bread and butter data analysis task, which is making a plot of some data.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:31.000
So I'm inside of Positron right now. I have possibly the silliest pane layout there ever could be, with Positron Assistant on the left-hand side, Posit Assistant in the middle, and then my console in plots on the right.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:36.000
So I'm going to ask Positron Assistant if it can make a plot with some data.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:43.000
This data is called forested. It's inside of an R package called forested.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:51.000
So the Positron Assistant will take a look at that data and then make a plot with it.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:59.000
It seemed like it didn't quite get the factor levels right on the first try, but then it was able to make a plot just fine.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:06.000
Once the agent finishes, it takes a look at the plot and then tells me what it sees in a couple sentences.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:14.000
I'll go ahead and clear this, and I would expect that we'll see a pretty similar thing from Posit Assistant.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:18.000
So I'll provide it the same prompt and we'll see what it does.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:24.000
Okay, so first it's taking a look at the forested data set.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:31.000
And after thinking a little bit, it's going to go ahead and make what I think is going to be a super similar plot.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:38.000
Okay, so it's made a plot of the longitude and latitude inside of this data.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:44.000
It realizes that it's looking at Washington state, and it describes the plot in a couple sentences.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:50.000
One thing you might notice here is that it's provided a few suggestions at the end.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:57.000
So this is where Positron Assistant sort of melds with the DataBot experience.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:04.000
DataBot users might recognize those suggestions at the end of data analysis questions,

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:08.000
where the model will sort of try to anticipate where to go next.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:16.000
And if we were doing this analysis not for the purposes of the demo, Posit Assistant can go in the sidebar.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:22.000
So you just have it there because then you can have Positron Assistant and Posit Assistant side by side, right?

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:28.000
Yeah, that's right. So in normal usage, I would probably keep Posit Assistant over here,

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:35.000
so that it's on the sidebar in the same way that Positron Assistant was, but you can sort of keep it wherever you wish.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:45.000
Okay, so for the most part, folks will experience Positron Assistant and Posit Assistant as pretty similar tools.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:49.000
But I wanted to call out a few ways where they diverge.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:55.000
The first one is the way that the agent interacts with tools.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:11:01.000
So tools allow the models to, for example, execute code or read package documentation,

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:06.000
fetch resources from the web, so on and so forth.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:13.000
Inside of Positron Assistant, the agent does support tools and it's able to retrieve information.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:19.000
But that information goes away once the agent has had the chance to react to it.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:25.000
And we've seen in our work on Posit Assistant that the agent behaves a bit more stably

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:31.000
when the conversation history is sort of append only, like the agent reacts to something,

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:36.000
and then in future turns, it's able to see what it was that it was reacting to.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:46.000
So this behavior of not persisting tool results in the conversation is just inherited from upstream in VS Code Copilot.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:55.000
But in Posit Assistant, this is our own stack, and we've decided to persist those tool call results inside of the history.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:02.000
There's also a few tools inside of Posit Assistant that Positron Assistant doesn't have.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:07.000
Those are web search, sub-agent orchestration, and mode switching.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:14.000
So I figured I might make use of a couple of these unique features to show something that is possible in Posit Assistant,

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:17.000
which is not possible in Positron Assistant.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:23.000
And that will be the agent customizing itself.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:31.000
So like I said, both Posit Assistant and Positron Assistant are able to support MCP.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:37.000
And I thought I could quickly demo Posit Assistant adding an MCP server to itself.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:42.000
So if I ask Posit Assistant, how do I add an MCP server?

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.000
The agent will choose to load a skill.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:52.000
This skill is called self-knowledge, and it sort of teaches Posit Assistant about itself.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:59.000
This is one of like 10 or so skills that Posit Assistant has available to it.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:07.000
So it will read that skill file, and then it looks like it's asked to read a reference inside of that skill.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:09.000
So I'll go ahead and approve that.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:16.000
And with that, the agent is able to learn how to configure itself.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:21.000
Okay, and then at the end of this response, it's provided me a link.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:25.000
We can share that in the description, but that is a real one.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:29.000
Those live inside of the skill file itself.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:37.000
Before I go any further, this next step is going to require the agent to do a bunch of stuff.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:42.000
And rather than clicking allow for each of those, I'm going to use something called YOLO mode,

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:50.000
which allows the agent to just work autonomously without me approving each of the tool calls.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:59.000
The next thing I'll do is provide some instructions to carry out a pretty difficult task with some vague instructions.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:06.000
I will ask, could you add the docs tools from the BTW-MCP server to this project?

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:09.000
So this one's sort of tricky.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:13.000
It's not clear from the question itself what BTW is.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:18.000
This is actually a package from my colleague, Garrick, and I.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:23.000
That allows, among other things, tools to read our package documentation.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:31.000
So one of the unique capabilities of Posit Assistant is that it can use web search.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:40.000
So as you can see, it searched for the BTW-MCP server docs tools along with some other bits in the query.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:46.000
It found the information it needed, and then it was able to configure itself.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:50.000
So with that knowledge of how its own settings work,

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:55.000
it was able to write its own JSON file and configure this server.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:15:01.000
So from now on, Posit Assistant will have these native tools to read our package documentation

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:04.000
rather than the ones that it uses typically.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:10.000
And that'll be across sessions and across projects, right?

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:12.000
Yeah, that's right.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:16.000
So in this setting, I asked it to write just for this project.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:21.000
So it wrote to, we can see here, dot Posit AI inside of my project.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:27.000
So this will kick in any time I start a new conversation inside of this project.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:32.000
We could have also asked it to apply it for the whole user space.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:38.000
And in that case, it would have written to tilde slash dot Posit AI.

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:41.000
Tilde slash dot Posit AI.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:43.000
Cool.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:51.000
So at a high level, Posit Assistant used a few capabilities here that are sort of unique.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:55.000
It has its own self-knowledge skills, so it knows how to configure itself

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:58.000
and what its UI looks like and things like that.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:03.000
It can use web search to find information online.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:09.000
It customized itself and then it used skills to do so.

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:14.000
So for now, Posit Assistant has skills while Positron Assistant doesn't,

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:17.000
but Positron Assistant will gain skills pretty soon.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:26.000
I'll call out two more features of Posit Assistant that aren't available in Positron Assistant.

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:29.000
The first one is sandboxing.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:37.000
So in Linux, macOS, and Windows, there's a sandbox mode inside of Posit Assistant

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:41.000
which shuts off access to the network.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:45.000
It disallows writing outside of the workspace.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:52.000
Okay, Sarah, I'm glad you asked whether these settings would apply across projects.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:59.000
One way we can sort of demo the sandbox is to try to get the agent to write outside of the file space

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:05.000
by making this MCP server apply across projects.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:10.000
So in order to do that, it would need to write to somewhere in the user's file space

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:16.000
other than the active project, but the sandbox will disallow the agent from doing that.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:22.000
So I can say, could you enable that across projects?

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:28.000
So in order to do that, it would need to write to the root of the file system,

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:34.000
but we can see that the agent is denied from writing that file

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:39.000
because the operation is not permitted due to the sandbox.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:45.000
So in order to actually execute that code, the agent has to go through this special route

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:52.000
where it provides a reason why that action is dangerous in order to bypass the sandbox.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:55.000
And so our usual YOLO mode isn't kicking in.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:18:01.000
Instead, the agent has to ask us if it wants to write outside of the usual.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:05.000
But it can read outside of the directory in sandbox mode.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:11.000
That's correct. Yeah, it can read outside of the directory other than sensitive files.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:15.000
Like a .env file or something.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:19.000
That's right. Yeah, like a .env file or secrets or something like that.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:26.000
The last thing I'll say about the difference between Positron Assistant and Posit Assistant

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:28.000
is the cost considerations.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:37.000
So there's a bunch of different ways that the conversation management differs between these two systems.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:40.000
So this isn't really an apples-to-apples comparison,

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:46.000
but I will just say we've spent a lot of time in Posit Assistant focused on cache efficiency.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:50.000
When agents have really good cache efficiency,

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:56.000
it means that most of the conversation is a cache hit rather than a cache miss.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:00.000
And cache hits are usually, depending on the provider,

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:05.000
priced at something like a tenth of the cost of cache misses.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:10.000
And so we've seen that Posit Assistant's cache efficiency is super strong.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:16.000
And there are some situations where Positron Assistant will miss the cache

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.000
in places where Posit Assistant wouldn't.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:24.000
The last difference that I was hoping we could cover before we wrap this video up

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:28.000
is a bit squishier and harder to demonstrate directly.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:33.000
But we've spent a good bit of time on the feel of Posit Assistant

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:35.000
and how we've prompted it.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:37.000
So Sarah and I have worked quite a bit on this.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:39.000
I was wondering if you could take this one on.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:46.000
I think the main thing that you might notice about Posit Assistant

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:50.000
is that because it combines, or in some way that combines,

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:53.000
data bot abilities and Positron Assistant abilities,

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:57.000
it has these two modes that it can be in,

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:02.000
where one is it's doing data analysis much in the same way that data bot does.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:07.000
And in that mode where it's doing data analysis,

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:10.000
that might be EDA, making visualizations, something like that.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:16.000
It knows that, or it's assuming that your goal is to understand the data.

00:20:17.211 --> 00:20:22.411
And so it does things a little bit differently than if it were just trying to get a task done.

00:20:22.411 --> 00:20:26.251
So it's supposed to only do a couple tool calls at a time. So it's only going to run little bits

00:20:26.251 --> 00:20:32.091
of code at a time before presenting you with the results of that code, a summary, and then

00:20:32.731 --> 00:20:39.051
giving you suggestions like we saw earlier. So it has this one mode, it does, you know,

00:20:39.051 --> 00:20:44.091
it's supposed to do three or fewer tool calls, regroup, give you suggestions. But then it has

00:20:44.091 --> 00:20:48.251
another mode where if it thinks you just want to get a task done, like you're refactoring,

00:20:48.891 --> 00:20:52.970
you know, all the code in your R package or something, and your goal is to complete the

00:20:52.970 --> 00:20:58.411
task, it's going to be more agentic, do more tool calls, get more stuff done, and interact

00:20:58.411 --> 00:21:04.010
with you a little bit differently. So Posit Assistant can do both of those things. I think

00:21:04.010 --> 00:21:08.650
in the past, like Positron Assistant sort of interacted one way and Data Bot interacted

00:21:08.650 --> 00:21:17.051
another. So Posit Assistant combines the two. And I think the other thing, I don't really know

00:21:17.051 --> 00:21:23.131
what it's like exactly for Positron Assistant, but for Posit Assistant, we've spent some time

00:21:23.131 --> 00:21:30.811
with the prompting so that it behaves in ways like we want it to produce statistically sound

00:21:30.811 --> 00:21:38.811
analyses. It has some prompting about, you know, robust statistical analyses. And for things like

00:21:38.811 --> 00:21:45.290
modeling, there's some information about best practices for predictive modeling, like data

00:21:45.290 --> 00:21:49.930
splitting, not immediately fitting on the test set, all of that. And then it also has a specific

00:21:49.930 --> 00:21:58.091
predictive modeling skill. And then I think also, just in general, we've instructed Posit Assistant

00:21:58.731 --> 00:22:06.010
to not do things like be overly flattering to your ideas, like avoid things like, oh, great analysis,

00:22:06.010 --> 00:22:12.491
or like great idea, and to, in general, be more straightforward. I'm not saying necessarily

00:22:12.491 --> 00:22:17.131
that Positron Assistant is like that, but Posit Assistant is definitely not supposed to, you know,

00:22:17.131 --> 00:22:24.491
be overly flattering, or do things like use a bunch of emojis, or like a bunch of bullets.

00:22:24.570 --> 00:22:28.970
It has a more straightforward, or at least it's supposed to have a more straightforward

00:22:28.970 --> 00:22:35.051
way of communicating with the user. Yeah. Anything you want to add to that?

00:22:35.610 --> 00:22:40.810
No, I think that's well said. I hope that those changes make the agent, you know, especially

00:22:40.810 --> 00:22:46.651
pleasant to interact with. We've really tried to iterate on it to the point where

00:22:47.450 --> 00:22:52.011
it's sort of a humble and measured collaborator. So hopefully that comes through to folks.

00:22:55.211 --> 00:22:59.051
With that, that is Positron Assistant versus Posit Assistant.

00:22:59.051 --> 00:23:03.291
Sarah, I appreciate you joining me for this one. Yeah, definitely.
